{
  "doc_id": "49708",
  "text": "Retinal vessels can be visualized through non-invasive means, such as funduscopy, angiography, and optical coherence tomography (OCT); thus, in the past decades, several studies have attempted to identify early changes serving as predictors of retinopathy, [CITATION_1] focusing on morphological characteristics, such as retinal vascular dimensions or functional characteristics, including blood flow rate, oxygenation, or leakage of systemically applied dyes, such as those used in fluorescein angiography. [CITATION_2] However, an effective biomarker for DR was not successfully identified. [CITATION_3] Indeed, results of the Wisconsin Epidemiologic Study of Diabetic Retinopathy (WESDR) [CITATION_4] and the New Jersey 725 study revealed no correlation between retinal vascular caliber and the risk of DR. [CITATION_5] It is uncertain whether continued use of the existing architectural and functional vascular measurements with more rigor would provide a reliable biomarker for early diagnosis of DR.",
